ejecting the focus on power common to American realists and liberals, the authors offer a novel analysis of influence. In the process, they differentiate influence from power and power from material resources. Their analysis shows why the United States, the greatest power the world has ever seen, is increasingly incapable of translating its power into influence. Reich and Lebow use their analysis to formulate a more realistic place for America in world affairs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBalance of powerxHistoryy21st century. 0aInternational relationsxHistoryy21st century. 0aWorld politicsy21st century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican liberals.  aAmerican realists.  aAsia.  aChina.  aEurope.  aEuropean initiatives.  aIraq.  aLibya.  aMexico.  aNorth Korea.  aRobert Kagan.  aSimon Reich.  aU.S. foreign policy.  aU.S. hegemony.  aUnited States.  aagenda setting.  acivilian protection.  acustodial economic functions.  acustodial economic management.  acustodianship.  adiplomacy.  aeconomic custodianship.  aeconomic instability.  afinancial crises.  aglobal capitalism.  aglobal economic system.  aglobal initiatives.  aglobal norms.  aglobal order.  aglobalization.  ahegemony.  ainfluence.  ainternational affairs.  ainternational relations theory.  ainternational relations.  ainternational system.  alandmines.  aleadership strategies.  amaterial capabilities.  amilitary power.  amultipowered world.  anegotiation.  aposthegemonic world.  aposthegemony.  apower sources.  apower.  asocial power.  avalues.1 aLebow, Richard Ned, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBoo